probably my favorite poem of all time... and it has more meaning for me now then ever before. 

weighing the dog

It is awkward for me and bewildering for him
as I hold him in my arms in the small bathroom,
balancing our weight on the shaky blue scale,

but this is the way to weigh a dog and easier
than training him to sit obediently on one spot
with his tongue out, waiting for a cookie.

With pencil and paper I subtract my weight
from our total to find out the remainder that is his,
and I start to wonder if there is an analogy here.

It could not have to do with my leaving you
though I never figured out what you amounted to
until I subtracted myself from our combination.

You held me in your arms more than I held you
through all those awkward and bewildering months
and now we are both lost in strange and distant neighborhoods.

(billy collins)

Its all about chaos. Think about it...

The big bang... the universe expands from an infinitesimally small singularity and superheated matter is tossed to the far corners. Atoms combine and mutate in the heat forming elements. elements group together in clouds which begin swirling and swirling spinning into tight super dense hot balls that explode into stars and send heavier elements out which crash together and become planets. in our solar system the third planet from the sun is a ball of molten iron. less dense elements rise to the surface of the planet where they cool harden, and then sink back down into the planet. hundreds of millions of years pass, the planet cools down. a radioactive element on the planet is at just the right temperature to create  a small strand of protein that mutates into a single celled organism that develops photosynthesis to survive. as a part of photosynthesis the organism absorbs carbon and produces oxygen. hundreds of millions of years pass. the planet has cooled, oxygen and nitrogen released from the planet have formed an atmosphere. there is rain. the rain collects in large pools. lighting strikes these pools and creates new protein. hundreds of millions of years pass, trilobites, hundreds of millions of years pass, fish, hundreds of millions of years pass, creatures take to land, millions of years pass, the planet experiences a boom of life. millions and millions and millions of years pass, dinosaurs come and go, millions of years pass, man sets foot on the planet, with his brain developed as the ultimate tool for survival. man names the planet earth. man does not understand earth so man creates god. men create war. men create beauty. men create philosophy and truly begin to think. men create science. science slowly reveals to men the way the world works. men become afraid when they realize that there is no god. men begin to discover that existence is pointless. science shows men that the universe will eventually collapse upon itself. men realize there is no such thing as free will because there is only one future, non existence. science reveals there is no such thing as free thought because all thoughts are chemical reactions in the brain that are part of a chain reaction that started with the big bang. All thought, every thought every man has ever had was meant to happen and had to happen. why? because of chaos. because of a random series of events. a random series of events that all men are trapped in. men call these random events "lives". god promises men an afterlife. god lies. god is a lie.there is no afterlife. there is only nothing-chaos-then nothing. and because everything will end, because everything will cease to exist, men accepted the fact that life is pointless, and that everything they do was simply contributing to the chaos and there was no way to escape it because everything that has happened and everything that will happen is chaos. philosophers gave up the pursuit for truth when they realized truth is chaos. they reasoned... "EVERYTHING IS CHAOS AND EVERYTHING IS FUCKED UP AND EVERYONE IS FUCKED UP AND EVERYTHING IS FUCKED". 
                     then man created love. and love worked for a while.
 
the end.

I am no longer interesting. 

I need change. 

something drastic...


The Art Of Drowning

I wonder how it all got started, this business
about seeing your life flash before your eyes
while you drown, as if panic, or the act of submergence,
could startle time into such compression, crushing
decades in the vice of your desperate, final seconds.

After falling off a steamship or being swept away
in a rush of floodwaters, wouldn't you hope
for a more leisurely review, an invisible hand
turning the pages of an album of photographs-
you up on a pony or blowing out candles in a conic hat.

How about a short animated film, a slide presentation?
Your life expressed in an essay, or in one model photograph?
Wouldn't any form be better than this sudden flash?
Your whole existence going off in your face
in an eyebrow-singeing explosion of biography-
nothing like the three large volumes you envisioned.

Survivors would have us believe in a brilliance
here, some bolt of truth forking across the water,
an ultimate Light before all the lights go out,
dawning on you with all its megalithic tonnage.
But if something does flash before your eyes
as you go under, it will probably be a fish,

a quick blur of curved silver darting away,
having nothing to do with your life or your death.
The tide will take you, or the lake will accept it all
as you sink toward the weedy disarray of the bottom,
leaving behind what you have already forgotten,
the surface, now overrun with the high travel of clouds.

                                          -Billy Collins

halo of silver sweaweed, the hair

while his eyes sleep, it stands up

I thought I'd take a snapshot of our happy moment. But the smiles quickly faded and the colors ran like tears down my waist onto my shoes leaving technicolor footprints as I walked away, examining my empty frame. 


When You Are Old
When you are old and grey and full of sleep,
And nodding by the fire, take down this book,
And slowly read, and dream of the soft look
Your eyes had once, and of their shadows deep;

How many loved your moments of glad grace,
And loved your beauty with love false or true,
But one man loved the pilgrim Soul in you,
And loved the sorrows of your changing face;

And bending down beside the glowing bars,
Murmur, a little sadly, how Love fled
And paced upon the mountains overhead
And hid his face amid a crowd of stars.
-William Butler Yeats
